Seminal quality prediction using logistic regression¶

Activation function¶

In [ ]:
import numpy as np


def sigmoid(z):
    return 1/(1 + np.exp(-z))
Loss/Cost function¶
  • Binary cross entory loss
  • Also resolved by logarithmic loss or log loss
  • The aim is to minimise this loss
  • L = −[𝑦log(𝑝)+(1−𝑦)log(1−𝑝)] since this is a binary classification task ( multiclass classification will be resolved differently)
In [ ]:
def binary_cross_entorypy_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    # Clip the predicted probabilities to prevent NaNs.
    y_pred = np.clip(y_pred, 1e-7, 1 - 1e-7)
    return -1 * np.sum(y_true*np.log(y_pred) + (1-y_true)*np.log(1-y_pred))

Model creation¶

In [ ]:
class SQModel():
    def __init__(self, lr=0.0099, iters=100):
        self.lr = lr
        self.iters = iters
        self.weights = None
        self.bias = None
        self.loss = np.array([])

    # Hypothesis of x
    def hx(self, w, X):
        bias = w[0]
        weights = w[1:]

        wX = np.array(X.dot(weights))
        z = bias + wX

        return sigmoid(z)

    def cost(self, w, X, Y):
        y_pred = self.hx(w, X)
        return binary_cross_entorypy_loss(Y, y_pred)

    def gradients(self, w, X, Y):
        y_pred = self.hx(w, X)
        g = np.array([])

        dww = -1 * np.sum(Y*(1-y_pred) - (1-Y)*y_pred)
        g = np.append(g, dww)

        for i in range(1, len(w)):
            dw = -1 * np.sum(Y*(1-y_pred)*X[:, i-1] - (1-Y)*y_pred*X[:, i-1])
            g = np.append(g, dw)

        return g

    # Optimize model parameters(weight and bias)
    # and minimize cost function using gradient descent
    def descent(self, X, Y):
        # Initialize weights to 1s, including bias
        n_features = X.shape[1]
        self.weights = w_new = w_prev = np.ones(n_features + 1)

        for iter in range(self.iters):
            w_prev = w_new
            w_new = np.array([])
            for i in range(len(w_prev)):
                wi = w_prev[i] - self.lr * self.gradients(w_prev, X, Y)[i]
                w_new = np.append(w_new, wi)

            loss = self.cost(w_prev, X, Y)
            self.loss = np.append(self.loss, loss)

            # print('\niter: ', iter)
            # print('w: ', w_prev)

            # TODO: ??? powr?
            if np.sum((w_new - w_prev)**2) < pow(10, -6):
                return w_new

        return w_new

    def fit(self, X, Y):
        self.weights = self.descent(X, Y)

    def predict(self, X):
        predictions = self.hx(self.weights, X)

        # TODO: (Improvement) Dynamically determine threshold
        threshold = 0.5
        y_pred = [0 if y < threshold else 1 for y in predictions]
        return y_pred

2. Principal Componet Analysis (PCA)

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
In [ ]:
X_standardized = (X - X.mean()) / X.std()
pca = PCA(n_components=X.shape[1])
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_standardized)

explained_variance_ratio = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
print("Explained Variance Ratio: {}".format(explained_variance_ratio))

# Identify the original columns with highest contributions to the PCA components
# Get the absolute values of the PCA components
abs_components = np.abs(pca.components_)
top_contributors = {}
for i, component in enumerate(abs_components):
    top_index = component.argmax()  # Index of the highest contributor
    top_contributors[i] = X.columns[top_index]

print("\nOrdered list of contributors: ", top_contributors)

# Compute the cumulative explained variance
cumulative_variances = np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
print("\nExplained Variance Ratio: {}".format(explained_variance_ratio))

# Create the bar plot for individual variances
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
bar = plt.bar(range(1, X.shape[1]+1), explained_variance_ratio,
              alpha=0.6, color='g', label='Individual Explained Variance')

# Create the line plot for cumulative variance
line = plt.plot(range(1, X.shape[1]+1), cumulative_variances, marker='*',
                linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, markersize=12, color='r',
                label='Cumulative Explained Variance')

# Adding percentage values on top of bars and dots
for i, (bar, cum_val) in enumerate(zip(bar, cumulative_variances)):
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height(), f'{explained_variance_ratio[i]*100:.1f}%',
             ha='center', va='bottom')
    plt.text(i+1, cum_val, f'{cum_val*100:.1f}%', ha='center', va='bottom')

# Aesthetics for the plot
plt.xlabel('Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Explained Variance')
plt.title('Explained Variance by Different Principal Components')
plt.xticks(range(1, X.shape[1]+1))
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.ylim(0, 1.1)  # extend y-axis limit to accommodate text labels
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Feature selection¶

We will look for the most relevant features in our dataset, ones which will allow us to reduce the dimensionality of the feature space. This can be beneficial to reduce overfitting as well.

Since ours is a classification problem, a Chi-squared (chi²) statistical test would probably be the most meangful for this analysis. But we have negative values in our dataset(devoid of any transformations). Nonetheless, we can make use of a

We will make use of these methods:

  1. Correlation matrix
  2. Chi-squared (chi²) statistical test with scikit-learn's SelectKBest
  3. Feature Importance

fit = selector.fit(X_t, Y)

Metrics¶

To measure the performance of our mode, we're going to use the below metrics to evaluating it:

Metric Description
Accuracy The accuracy score descibes how accurately the model has been able to correctly classify/predict with new data.
Precision Identifies the proportion of positive predictions that are actually positive, for a certain class
Recall This is a measure of how the model correctly identifies the True Positives
F1 Score Assentially, the F1 score helps us to better perceive the tension between the Precision and Recall scores. It is the harmonic mean of precision and recall
Log loss The logarithmic loss evaluates the differences between the predicted probabilities and the actual binary outcomes, helping to understand the model's accuracy
ROC & AUC This metric evaluates the ability of a binary classification model to distinguish between the positive and negative classes across various threshold settings
In [ ]:
from sklearn import metrics
In [ ]:
# Implement accuracy score calculator
def accuracy_score(y_pred, y_true):
    acc_score = np.sum(y_pred==y_true) / len(y_true) * 100
    return "{:.0f}%".format(acc_score)
In [ ]:

Confusion matrix¶

The Confusion Matrix provides a comprehensive summary of the performance of a classification model by presenting the counts of true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative predictions made by the model on a test dataset.

In [ ]:
confusion_matrix = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

class_names = [0, 1]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
tick_marks = np.arange(len(class_names))
plt.xticks(tick_marks, class_names)
plt.yticks(tick_marks, class_names)

sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix), annot=True, cmap="YlGnBu", fmt='g')
